  "text": "Recently we have developed an adaptively compressed exchange operator formulation (ACE) [CITATION_1] , which reduces the cost for solving Hartree-Fock-like equations from a different and yet more general perspective. The key observation is that we only need to find an effective operator B so that Bv = Bv is satisfied for v ∈ span V , where V = [v 1 , . . . , v n ]. B can be constructed to be of strict rank n, and hence the computational cost of Bv is much smaller than that of Bv. Note that the subspace span V is precisely the solution for (1.1) and is not known a priori. Therefore B needs to be constructed in an adaptive manner. Starting from some initial guess V (0) , we will obtain a sequence V converges to span V , then in the limit the compressed operator B[V (k) ] will agree with B on span V , and the eigenvalue problem (1.1) is solved without loss of accuracy.",
